    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-09-02T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-09-02T22:00:00-05:00" n="375"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d375">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 E.W./9–244: Circular telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Certain
                            <gloss type="to">American Diplomatic and Consular Officers</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="84" xml:id="d375fn84">At Ankara (for repetition to Istanbul), Lisbon,
                        Rome, Stockholm; and paraphrase as 3042, September 4, to Bern.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-09-02T23:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 2, 1944—11 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Department considers that until the situation is clarified by Rumanian and
                    Bulgarian acceptance of Allied armistice terms and until the status of the
                    governments of these two countries is ascertained your attitude toward their
                    diplomatic officials should remain unchanged.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>[There are a few additional papers printed in <ref
                            target="frus1945Malta#pg_237">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, The Conferences at Malta and
                            Yalta, 1945, pages 237</ref>–<ref target="frus1945Malta#pg_248"
                            >248</ref>, which present summary descriptions on what the general
                        Balkan policy of the United States had come to be at the close of the year
                        1944; on consideration of the American position on the Allied Control
                        Commissions in Rumania, Bulgaria, and Hungary; and on the attitude taken
                        toward the principal problems that had arisen in each of these three
                        countries.]</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
